<LP>
   BUDGET NEGOTIATORS are considering proposals to curb
itemized tax deductions, including those for
mortgage-interest payments, charitable giving and state and
local tax payments. The idea of restricting itemized
deductions has emerged because of Democratic demands that any
tax package hit the wealthy harder than other groups.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   AT&amp;T's profit slipped 6% in the second quarter, reflecting
lower longdistance revenue and sluggish equipment sales. But
the company said it still expects record 1990 earnings.
   ---
   Fujitsu is discussing buying control of International
Computers Ltd., Britain's biggest computer maker. It would be
the first big move by a Japanese computer firm into Europe.
   ---
   PPG Industries agreed to pay New Jersey $80 million to
clean up toxic chromium wastes, as well as a $2.5 million
fine. PPG had been threatened with lawsuits over the wastes.
   ---
   American Express earnings rose only 1.1% in the second
quarter, weighed down by results at its Shearson brokerage
unit. Shearson's revenue slumped 20% in the quarter.
   ---
   The Resolution Trust Corp. said it holds 483 junk-bond
issues in the portfolio it inherited in the S&amp;L crisis.
Analysts said the portfolio may be worth only 50 cents on the
dollar.
   ---
   Grumman said its top executive, John O'Brien, 60, resigned
unexpectedly for personal reasons.
   ---
   Iraq's aggressive stance is raising new questions about
next week's OPEC meeting in Geneva, and about the
organization's future leadership.
   ---
   Unisys' net income plunged 78% in the second quarter, as
its international growth slowed while domestic computer sales
remained depressed.
   ---
   U.S. Shoe said falling sales at its Lenscrafters unit will
result in lower second-quarter earnings. U.S. Shoe's stock
fell $4.25, closing at $18.
   ---
   A bill to shift power to the SEC from commodities
regulators is in trouble, and backers in the Senate are
scrambling to find a compromise.
   ---
   Short interest fell 2.8% on the Big Board in the month
ended July 13, but rose 4.2% on the American Exchange.
   ---
   Three Baby Bell companies,  Nynex, BellSouth and
Ameritech, reported solid gains in second-quarter profits.
But Southwestern Bell said its earnings were flat, and
Pacific Telesis posted an 8.9% decline.
   ---
   Alan Bond said he will resign as chairman of his flagship
company if investors approve a restructuring aimed at saving
the Australian entrepreneur's debt-heavy corporate empire.
   ---
   Two big waste-hauling firms reported higher profits for
the June quarter. Waste Management's net income increased
26%, while Browning-Ferris posted a 16% gain.
   ---
